Step 6 — Inside the loop: capture the trimmed current BU name
This solves the item() collision problem I mentioned earlier.

Inside the new Apply to each, click Add an action
Search Compose → add it
Rename to Current_BU_Name
Inputs (fx expression):

toLower(trim(item()))
This lowercases AND trims, killing both whitespace and case issues at once.

Step 7 — Inside the loop: Filter array against the SP BU list

Still inside For each BU name, below Current_BU_Name, click Add an action
Search Filter array → add it
Rename to Find_BU_in_SP
Configure:

From: the SharePoint BU list array (same source the old Find_BU_lookup_ID used — the value field from the upstream SP Get items)
Click Edit in advanced mode
Replace the entire expression with:



@equals(toLower(trim(item()?['BUName'])), outputs('Current_BU_Name'))
This compares lowercased+trimmed BUName on the SP side against the already-lowercased+trimmed value from Compose. Both sides normalized → matches reliably.

Step 8 — Inside the loop: check if a match was found, append the ID

Below Find_BU_in_SP, click Add an action
Search Condition → add it
Configure:

Left side: fx → length(body('Find_BU_in_SP'))
Operator: is greater than
Right side: 0


In the "If yes" branch:

Add action → Append to array variable
Name: BU_IDs_Array
Value: fx →



     first(body('Find_BU_in_SP'))?['ID']

In the "If no" branch:

Optional but recommended: add a Compose called Unmatched_BU with input outputs('Current_BU_Name') so you can see in run history which BUs failed to match. Helps with data cleanup later.




Step 9 — Use the array when creating/updating the SP item
This is back in the original "Create item" / "Update item" action where you saw the BU Id - 1 field.

Open that action
Find the BU Id field (the multi-value lookup)
Delete whatever's currently in there (the if(greater(length(...))) expression)
Click fx and enter:

variables('BU_IDs_Array')

If you get a "must be an object" error when running, change it to:

{
  "results": @{variables('BU_IDs_Array')}
}
(Some SP connector versions want the results wrapper for multi-lookup fields. Try without first; add the wrapper if it complains.)

Step 10 — Test

Save the flow
Run it manually (or trigger via your normal mechanism)
Check run history
Click into For each BU name → you should see one iteration per BU
Each iteration: Current_BU_Name shows the cleaned BU name, Find_BU_in_SP body should now have a matching row, Append fires
Final BU_IDs_Array should look like [3, 7] (or whatever the SP BU list IDs are)
Open the created/updated SharePoint item and verify both BUs are populated in the lookup column
